<div id="review_32510072" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/32510072" />
    <a title="Anna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/417669-anna"><img alt="Anna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1282868497p2/417669.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/32510072?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anna" href="/user/show/417669-anna">Anna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780553575491" href="/book/show/359390.Holy_Fire">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">people looking for smart sci fi premises and details (but not characters)</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer32510072" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7112440356238304014">Long on ideas, short on narrative. Sterling should be tapped to think up settings and backgrounds on a sci-fi tv series, or an ambitious futuristic film. Case in point: in <i>Holy Fire</i>, he projects the story past decades of plagues to imagine a medical-industrial complex run by &quot;gerontocrats.&quot; A fine, not implausible notion. But Sterling&apos;s real strength is to extrapolate from this general premise, having Indonesia become the richest, healthiest nation in the world after the plague years (as an isla</span>
  <span id="freeText7112440356238304014" style="display:none">Long on ideas, short on narrative. Sterling should be tapped to think up settings and backgrounds on a sci-fi tv series, or an ambitious futuristic film. Case in point: in <i>Holy Fire</i>, he projects the story past decades of plagues to imagine a medical-industrial complex run by "gerontocrats." A fine, not implausible notion. But Sterling's real strength is to extrapolate from this general premise, having Indonesia become the richest, healthiest nation in the world after the plague years (as an island nation, it was immune to the devastation). The final stroke of imaginative genius is that Indonesia then purchased Indianapolis from the poverty-striken United States, and used it for no-risk architectural experimentation. This small detail is more interesting than 100 pages of Mia/Maya's search for the "holy fire" of youthful creativity--ostensibly the novel's central plot. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7112440356238304014" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


