<div id="review_1521898555" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1521898555" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2579781-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1354556365p2/2579781.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1521898555?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/2579781-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780553575491" href="/book/show/359390.Holy_Fire">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2579781-paul?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2579781-paul?shelf=scifi">scifi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2579781-paul?shelf=cyberpunk">cyberpunk</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1521898555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6293363435503110052">Bruce Sterling is an excellent writer, which is why this book, which is not one of his better ones, is still quite good. It is partially an exercise in world-building, but mostly focuses on exploring some of the effects that a certain form of post-humanism could have on the character of certain people.<br/><br/>In a lot of ways, it reminds me of William Gibson&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/series/50543-blue-ant' rel='nofollow noopener'>Blue Ant</a> trilogy, though set further in the future and with a more decidedly science-fiction plot. Similar to the Blue Ant trilogy, the main char</span>
  <span id="freeText6293363435503110052" style="display:none">Bruce Sterling is an excellent writer, which is why this book, which is not one of his better ones, is still quite good. It is partially an exercise in world-building, but mostly focuses on exploring some of the effects that a certain form of post-humanism could have on the character of certain people.<br /><br />In a lot of ways, it reminds me of William Gibson's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/series/50543-blue-ant" rel="nofollow noopener">Blue Ant</a> trilogy, though set further in the future and with a more decidedly science-fiction plot. Similar to the Blue Ant trilogy, the main character is driven to explore many new subcultures across several countries that she was previously unfamiliar with.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />One thing that's interesting to me is the seemingly deliberate uncertainty about how much Maya/Mia's treatment <i>worked</i> and how much the personality change was due to the treatment rather than because she wanted to make the change and was using the treatment as an excuse. She obviously was flirting with the idea of living a different life before the change, and afterwards had moments of candor where she admitted to herself that she was hamming it up a bit, but it also seems that her reaction was a not-unusual side effect of the treatment, and she was never able to settle down again afterwards.<br /><br />I imagine that sort of uncertainty is largely how it would play out in reality as well. Given a fancy new 20 year old body at age 90, I imagine many people would take it as a chance to live their lives completely differently, and once unleashed would find it hard to go back to a life of restraint; but on the other hand anything that involves massive changes in your hormones and the growth of a bunch of new brain tissue is likely going to have psychological effects as well. In some ways, it's a poorly formed question to imagine that there is an essential "self" that would be separable from such a treatment.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />It's not a high-speed thriller or a mystery, just a character study in an interesting slightly post-human world. If you're into the cyberpunk and especially post-cyberpunk aesthetic, it's worth a read (though obviously if you're into that you, like me, will eventually work your way through Bruce Sterling's entire back catalog, so there's no need for my endorsement here).<br /><br /><b>3.5 of 5 stars</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="6293363435503110052" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

